Data Analysis Project - Matteo Fiore¶

The aim of this project is to try to predict the matches of the current Serie A season. More specifically, if a team is going to win, draw or lose a match based on the probabilities computed with the SPI, taking into considerations also where the team is playing (i.e. home or away).

This research work will start from the idea of the SPI, i.e. ESPN's Soccer Power Index. The research and idea behind this index can be found here: https://fivethirtyeight.com/methodology/how-our-club-soccer-predictions-work/. Moreover, the index is measuring a team's relative likelihood of victory if a competitive match were to be held.

All in all, the idea is to use the data that helped the researchers to come up with the SPI and compare the predictions made using the SPI. To do so, I divided my research project in 4 parts:

  1. Data Exploration where I will download and describe the dataframe features; I will remove some features and add some new ones
  2. Training and evaluation using Logistic Regression and SVM where I will perform some classification analysis
  3. Conclusions where I will evaluate the outcome of the previous step
  4. Critical Assessment where I will illustrate strength and possible improvements of this project

The question that I will try to answer are these:

  1. Are we able to predict the future based on past events?
  2. Will the obtained results be accurate?
  3. Which machine learning model is better for predicting the outcome of a match?

As pinpointed before, in this project I will try to predict whether a team is going to win/lose/draw a match when the team isplaying as the home team or when is playing as the away team. It is essential to remember that in football the outcome of the match is decided based on the number of goals scored (or not scored by a team). Therefore, it is important to keep in mind that the dataframe does not contain neither information about the current status of the teams nor what happened during the match, thus including red cards, referee's mistakes, injuries etc.

These missing information may be a potential problem for the overall accuracy. Nevertheless, these variable are somehow "included" in the match outcome. Therefore, for the moment it is not a priority to insert these variable in the current dataframe.

We need to add an important feature to the past result dataframe: the result. To be more accurate, I will insert as columns: points gained by both teams. To do this I will analyse the goal scored which can be found as values of the columns "home_teams_goals" (which represents the goal scored by the home team) and "away_team_goals" (which represents the goal scored by the away team). The points that a team can gain follows this scale:

  • 0 -> lose (i.e. the other team scores more goal)
  • 1 -> draw (i.e. both teams have the same goal scored, thus including a 0-0 result)
  • 3 -> win (i.e. the team scores more goal than its opponent)
In [ ]:
def home_points(df):
    if(df['home_team_goals'] > df['away_team_goals']):
        return 3
    elif (df['away_team_goals'] > df['home_team_goals']):
        return 0
    else:
        return 1


def away_points(df):
    if(df['away_team_goals'] > df['home_team_goals']):
        return 3
    elif (df['home_team_goals'] > df['away_team_goals']):
        return 0
    else:
        return 1


serie_a_matches_played['points_home'] = serie_a_matches_played.apply(
    home_points, axis=1)
serie_a_matches_played['points_away'] = serie_a_matches_played.apply(
    away_points, axis=1)

Training and evaluation using Logistic Regression and Support Vector Machines¶

The goal of this project is to to predict the winning team (home team or away team) based on features such as the probabilities of winning, tie or lose and the projected score of each team. I will use: Logistic Regression(LR) and Support Vector Machines(SVM) to train a model. Since this is a classification problem, the variable I want to predict(winning team) has three possible outcomes (without any specific order).

The possible outcomes are:

  • 1 if the home team wins
  • 2 if the away team wins
  • 0 if there is a draw among the two teams

The choice of these numbers (1,2,0) it is very similar to the one used for the classic betting system in Italy (1,2,X).

All in all, this classification problem is multinomial, as there are more than 2 possible outcomes, therefore it is fundamental to adapt the way I will predict the values with Logistic Regression and Support Vector Machines.

For Logistic Regression I will use Multinomial Logistic Regression method to generalize the Logistic Regression to this multiclass problem.

In the case of SVM, it will also be adapted to a multinomial model by using a one vs rest. I choose "one vs rest" instead of "one vs one" because it is less costly in terms of computation.

Before starting using Logistic Regression and Support Vector Machines, I will need to insert the column "winning team" in the dataframe. To have a more accurate view, I will create two different dataframes, as I am interesting in the results when Napoli is playing as the home team or when is playing as the away team. Therefore, I will filter the dataframe of matches played by the team and the I will insert the "winning team" column.

In [ ]:
serie_a_matches_played_home_team = serie_a_matches_played[(
    serie_a_matches_played['home_team'] == 'Napoli')]
serie_a_matches_played_home_team.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
serie_a_matches_played_home_team["winning team"] = np.where(
    serie_a_matches_played_home_team['points_home'] > serie_a_matches_played_home_team['points_away'], 1, np.where(serie_a_matches_played_home_team['points_home'] < serie_a_matches_played_home_team['points_away'], 2, 0))

serie_a_matches_played_away_team = serie_a_matches_played[(
    serie_a_matches_played['away_team'] == 'Napoli')]

serie_a_matches_played_away_team["winning team"] = np.where(
    serie_a_matches_played_away_team['points_home'] > serie_a_matches_played_away_team['points_away'], 1, np.where(serie_a_matches_played_away_team['points_home'] < serie_a_matches_played_away_team['points_away'], 2, 0))

model_svc2 = SVC(kernel='rbf', C=1)

o_vs_r_away.fit(X_train2, y_train2)

y_pred2 = o_vs_r_away.predict(X_test2)

Evaluation and compairison of the two models¶

To evaluate the performances of the SVM and LR models I will use three different metrics:

  • F1_Score which shows us how much inaccuracy we should expect from the forecast on average
  • Accuracy Score which evaluates the accuracy score for a set of predicted labels against the true labels
  • Cross Validation (CV) which is a procedure used to estimate the skill of the model on new data

Now, I will use the process of cross-validation. It involves training a model on several subsets of data and then assessing its performance on the remaining data. The results are shown as mean accuracy plus or minus standard deviation.

In [ ]:
scores_svm = cross_val_score(model_svc, X_svm, y_svm, cv=5)
print("Cross-validation score SVM home: {:.2f} +/- {:.2f}".format(scores_svm.mean(), scores_svm.std()))

scores_svm = cross_val_score(model_svc2, X_svm2, y_svm2, cv=5)
print("Cross-validation score SVM away: {:.2f} +/- {:.2f}".format(scores_svm.mean(), scores_svm.std()))

scores_rf = cross_val_score(model, X_lg_home, y_lg_home, cv=5)
print("Cross-validation score Logistic Regression home: {:.2f} +/- {:.2f}".format(scores_rf.mean(), scores_rf.std()))

scores_rf = cross_val_score(model_away, X_lg_away, y_lg_away, cv=5)
print("Cross-validation score Logistic Regression away: {:.2f} +/- {:.2f}".format(scores_rf.mean(), scores_rf.std()))

Cross-validation score SVM home: 0.66 +/- 0.01
Cross-validation score SVM away: 0.66 +/- 0.04
Cross-validation score Logistic Regression home: 0.64 +/- 0.02
Cross-validation score Logistic Regression away: 0.68 +/- 0.05

From the Cross-validation we gained the following insights:

  • The cross-validation scores' standard deviation is reasonably low, showing that the models' performance is consistent across various data subsets
  • It seems that the LR is slightly better in predicting the away team compared to SVM, whereas the LR and SVM shows close scores for the home team

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, it is important to point out that the performances of the model are affected also by the team that we are analysing and that there are too many variables that we cannot consider for having a generalized model for every team.

Nevertheless, according to the research results we can answer the research questions presented at the beginning:

  1. Are we able to predict the future based on past events?

    It is still very difficult to answer this question, however the obtained results are promising and there is room for improvements.

  2. Will the obtained results be accurate?

    The accuracy will depend on the team that we are analysing. In the case presented in this project, the SVM model has a higher F1-score for predicting whether a team is going to win/lose/draw while playing as the home team compared to LR model Whereas the LR has a higher F1-score for predicting whether a team is going to win/lose/draw while playing as the away team.

  3. Which machine learning model is better for predicting the outcome of a match?

    Since the results change according to the team of interest, it is still not clear which model among SVM or LR is the best. Nevertheless, the obtained results have shown that a solution could be to use SVM for predicting whether a team is going to win/lose/draw while playing as the home team and use LR for predicting whether a team is going to win/lose/draw while playing as the away team.

Critical Assessment¶

All in all, considering the features included in the dataframe, the obtained performances using different algorithms for predicting the goals scored by each team is satisfactory.

Nevertheless, there is still room for improvement.

The performances are still somehow inconsistent. Overall, the values of the score may change according to the team we are analysing for the following reasons:

  • Some teams have not played the same championship every year, thus because of the relegation process
  • The team's performances have been affected by numerous situations that could have not been depicted in the dataframe (injuries, mental issues, underperformance, etc.)
  • The team's performances are contradictory, therefore predicting goal scored or points gained leads to irregular results

One of the possible future work could be to find a dataframe containing the statistics about the players of the team and the other key events that are happening in a match such as injuries, red or yellow cards, etc. Thus, to find out the key players and how their performances influence the way the team performed in the match and possibly, how it can perform in the future.
